Plotting Distributions

Gabriel Odom

8/30/2018

Random variables in R are shown on https://stat.ethz.ch/R-manual/R-devel/library/stats/html/Distributions.html

There are two functions we will use: hist() and plot(density()). There is another function, summary() which will give us the mean and 5-number summary of a numeric vector.

Continuous Random Variables

The Normal Distribution

Sample Size of 10000

# Draw Random Sample: sqrt(5) ~= 2.24
xFullN <- rnorm(10000, mean = 2, sd = sqrt(5))

# Histogram
hist(xFullN)

# Summary
summary(xFullN)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
## -6.4425  0.4603  1.9895  2.0012  3.5196  9.9356
var(xFullN)
## [1] 5.027125
# Density Plots
density(xFullN)
## 
## Call:
##  density.default(x = xFullN)
## 
## Data: xFullN (10000 obs.);   Bandwidth 'bw' = 0.3198
## 
##        x                y            
##  Min.   :-7.402   Min.   :1.470e-06  
##  1st Qu.:-2.828   1st Qu.:1.374e-03  
##  Median : 1.747   Median :2.276e-02  
##  Mean   : 1.747   Mean   :5.460e-02  
##  3rd Qu.: 6.321   3rd Qu.:1.056e-01  
##  Max.   :10.895   Max.   :1.747e-01
plot(density(xFullN))

# Scatterplots
plot(xFullN)

Sample Size of 5

The Students \(t\) Distribution

Sample Size of 10000

# Draw Random Sample: sqrt(5) ~= 2.24
xFullSt <- rt(n = 10000, df = 4)

# Histogram
hist(xFullSt)

# Summary
summary(xFullSt)
##       Min.    1st Qu.     Median       Mean    3rd Qu.       Max. 
## -16.147203  -0.742198   0.001952  -0.010872   0.755701  19.074947
var(xFullSt)
## [1] 2.106971
# Density Plots
plot(density(xFullSt))

# Scatterplot
plot(xFullSt)
